				<dateline>Sunday 29.th June<date when="1862-06-29"/>. </dateline>
				<p>It was <name type="weather">warm</name> and we had a <name type="weather"
						>shower</name> this evening. About noon the Colonel sent for the Commanders
					of Companies and read our orders - to be ready at 8 hours notice to march. 60
					rounds of <objectName type="equipment">cartridge</objectName> &amp; 30,000 in
					the <objectName type="transportation">wagons</objectName> - 3 days provisions in
						<objectName type="equipment"> haversacks</objectName> - 4 on <objectName
						type="transportation">wagons</objectName> the latter only to be <objectName
						type="food">coffee</objectName>, <objectName type="food">hard
						bread</objectName>, and <objectName type="food">salt</objectName>. To take
					none but those are capable of doing and rapid marching: <objectName
						type="equipment">tents</objectName> to be left standing - guards to be of
					convalescents, who are to strike ten<objectName type="equipment"/>ts, and have
					them taken to town, to be put upon a <objectName type="transportation"
						>schooner</objectName> to be designated. This about the substance - only
					officers are not to be allowed any transportation. They may have one <objectName
						type="transportation">packhorse</objectName> to regiment, but it is to be
					considered private property though allowed to go along in the <objectName
						type="transportation">train</objectName>. 4 camp <objectName
						type="equipment">kettles</objectName> &amp; 4 mess <objectName
						type="equipment">pans</objectName> allowed to a company &amp; 3 <objectName
						type="transportation">wagons</objectName> to a Regiment. This looks like a
					mysterious raid somewhere, and we have spent the day in various discussions - we
					know about as much about it as we always did - is probably a diversion in favor
					of <persName> McClellan</persName>. We had a sermon this evening by
						<persName>Mr. Mallory</persName> he standing before his <objectName
						type="equipment"> tent</objectName> and we seated on the <objectName
						type="nature">grass</objectName>. I noticed an unusually large attendance,
					which probably the prospects of a march effected. It put me in mind of
						<persName>Isaac Beck</persName>, one of my company, as he told the story
					himself, at the battle of <placeName cert="high" key="Camden"
						ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnpl008"
							>Camden<precision match="@ref" precision="high"/></placeName>, in the
					midst of it, <objectName type="equipment">bullets</objectName> raining all
					around, he pulled out his <objectName type="equipment">handkerchief</objectName>
					to wipe the <objectName type="body">sweat</objectName> off his <objectName
						type="body">face</objectName>, &amp; jerked some <objectName
						type="equipment">cards</objectName> out, which fell on the ground. He looked
					at them awhile and thought it would be a bad thing if he were shot, and was
					found with the <objectName type="equipment">cards</objectName> in his
						<objectName type="clothes">jacket</objectName>, &amp; he was going to throw
					them away - when the thoughts struck him he had just paid the Sutler 50 cents
					for them &amp; he thought he would risk it a while yet anyhow - so he picked up
					those that fell on the ground. He told it in a funny dutch way. I remember at
						<placeName key="Roanoke Island"
						ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnpl076"
						> Roanoke<precision match="@ref" precision="medium"/></placeName> we were
					among the last regiments that moved up, and the road was scattered full of
						<objectName type="equipment">cards</objectName>. <persName cert="medium"
						key="William Allison"
						ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper082"
						type="real">Billy Allison</persName> remarked that we're getting
					conscientious - This was as we were going into the battle. I sort of hate this
					very rapid march, this <name type="weather">hot weather</name> - but as I have
					stood others pretty severe I know I can go through it. We were mustered as of
					tomorrow by the Col. <persName key="Capt. William H. Blair"
						ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper179"
						>Capt. Blair's</persName> company has been sent for - their <objectName
						type="equipment">baggage</objectName> arrived this evening.</p>
			</div>
		</body>
	</text>
